The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, March 30, 2004 				 Govt sets steep targets for oil majors
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 				 	 Push factor																								New Delhi, March 29: The petroleum ministry has raised significantly the financial targets for the national oil and gas companies for 2004-05.																								Hindustan Petroleum (HPCL) will be targeting a sales turnover of Rs 55,805 crore for 2004-05 compared with the Rs 53,780 crore turnover achieved in 2003-04. The downstream oil company has also agreed to extend the initiative of branding retail outlets as Club HP to 1,800 outlets where outstanding care will be offered to customers.																								Oil India Ltd (OIL) has been set a target of achieving a sales turnover of Rs 2,976.25 crore, which is Rs 266 crore higher than the current years turnover of Rs 2,710.26 crore.																								According to the MoU, OIL is expected to produce 3.21 million tonnes of crude during 2004-05 against the current years target of 3 million tonnes. The target for the companys gas output has also been raised to 2,059 million cubic metres (MCM) from 1,815 MCM in the current fiscal.																								Gail has been set the target of a higher gross margin of Rs 3,073 crore for 2004-05, which is Rs 490 crore higher than Rs 2,583.7 crore the company would report for 2003-04. 																								Gail has been set a natural gas sales target of 58.03 million standard cubic metres per day, while the target for production of petrochemicals has been raised to 1,82,779 tonnes from 2,60,000 tonnes achieved during 2003-04. 																								Bharat Petroleum (BPCL) has been set the target of increasing the crude throughput of its Mumbai refinery to 8.7 million tonnes from the current level of 8.28 million tonnes. The thrust of the BPCL MoU has been enlarged to encompass the key parameters on quality assurance and customer satisfaction. 																								Emphasis has been laid on speedy completion of major projects, including the Mumbai refinery modernisation project and the commissioning of the LPG plants at Vijayawada and Bangalore. HPCL has agreed to complete the green fuels and emission control projects at a cost of Rs 1,152 crore at its Mumbai refinery and Rs 1,635 crore at its Vizag refinery by August 2004 and March 2005, respectively.																								The MoUs were signed with the respective CMDs of these companies and petroleum secretary B. K. Chaturvedi.
